<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,500,941,967]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Erythrolamprus maryellenae</emphasis>
Dixon, 
<number box="[597,656,941,967]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" value="1985.0">1985</number>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,656,941,1000]" box="[151,384,975,1000]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">(Figs. 14.7 and 27.2)</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1436,1047,1216]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
Recorded at a single locality in the 
<taxonomicName authority="Plateau" authorityName="Plateau" box="[554,778,1047,1072]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Podostemaceae" genus="Diamantina" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Diamantina Plateau</taxonomicName>
, municipality of Mucugê, Bahia State, 
<quantity box="[1222,1294,1048,1072]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.83" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="m" value="983.0">983 m</quantity>
elevation. It was previously known only in the Cerrado region and is considered endemic to this domain, found mostly in riparian, open areas (
<bibRefCitation author="Nogueira" box="[398,646,1119,1144]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" refString="Nogueira, C., Colli, G. R., Costa, G. &amp; Machado, R. B. (2010) Diversidade de repteis Squamata e evolucao do conhecimento faunistico no Cerrado. In: Diniz, I. R., Marinho-Filho, J., Machado, R. B. &amp; Cavalcanti, R. B. (Eds.), Cerrado: conhecimento cientifico quantitativo como subsidio para acoes de conservacao. Editora UNB, Brasilia, pp. 333 - 375." type="book chapter" year="2010">
Nogueira 
<emphasis box="[515,568,1119,1144]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[585,646,1120,1144]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" value="2010.0">2010</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Its presence in our study region seems to be restricted to 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">campos rupestres</emphasis>
and other cerrado associated grasslands in isolated highlands inside the Caatinga. It has terrestrial and semi aquatic habits, is diurnal, and feeds on vertebrates (
<bibRefCitation author="Dixon" box="[784,922,1191,1216]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" refString="Dixon, J. R. (1989) A key and checklist to the Neotropical snake genus Liophis with country lists and maps. Smithsonian Herpetological Information, 79, 1 - 39. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 23317515.79.1" type="journal article" year="1989">
Dixon 
<number box="[863,922,1192,1216]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[933,1009,1192,1215]" name="France" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">França</collectingCountry>
<emphasis box="[1016,1064,1191,1216]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[1079,1140,1192,1216]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" value="2008.0">2008</number>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
